[Student "S"]
{You would really like to have a transfer bid in this situation, to make South bid \Hs.

But you don't have one, so you just bid 4\H yourself.

North plays 4\H. East leads the \ST. You play low in dummy and East holds the trick. He continues the suit and West takes the \SQ and then plays the \SA.

Loser List: \S = 2 : \H = 1 : \D = 0 : \C = 1 :: Total = 4

You've already lost the 2 \Ss. If East has the \HK you might avoid a loser there. You don't have a winner on which to discard the \C loser. 

If West has the \HK it will have to be a singleton to help you, so it is more logical to play East for the \HK.  But if East does have the \HK it will do you no good to ruff West's \SA, East will over-ruff and you would still have that \C loser. 

So do it this way instead. Discard the \C loser on West's \SA! Another \S from West won't hurt you since dummy would be able to over-ruff East. Whatever West plays you can win, then finesse East out of his \HK.

It was said earlier that you didn't have a winner on which you could discard the \C loser.

That was true, so instead you were able to discard it on a loser! }
[Play "W"]ST

