[Student "S"]
{With no 4-card Major suit you respond 2\D to partner's Stayman bid. Partner now bids 2NT.  

With no 4-card Major suit you respond 2\D to partner's Stayman bid. Partner now bids 2NT. 

With a full 17 points you accept partner's game invitation and bid 3NT.

West plays 3NT. North leads the \S6 on which South plays the \SQ.

Winner List: \S = 1 : \H = 2 : \D = 2 : \C = 1 :: Total = 6

You need 3 more tricks, obviously coming from the \C suit.

But the burning question right now is what do you do at trick one. Do you win or hold up? 

You should assume that North holds the \SK.

If you take the \SA right now your \S J 5 will provide a second stopper if it is North who gets the lead. However, if South gets the lead he will play through your holding and you may lose 4 \S tricks.

If you hold up you can expect South to play another \S through your \S A J and North will then establish the suit. However, in doing so he will remove any \S held by South.

The answer key lies in the \C suit. You will be finessing through North, so South is the only defender who can get the lead in \Cs. Therefore you must hold up on \Ss until the third round.

If you win the first \S South will play a \S through your \S J 5 when he wins the \CK. North will then swamp you with \Ss.

But, if you hold up your \SA until the third round, South will have no \S left when he wins the \CK.}
[Play "W"]S6

